# Profiling Guide

> CPU, memory, and SQL profiling for **{{ project_name }}**.

---

## Overview

The profiling subsystem provides three core profilers plus on-demand
request-level middleware. All profilers are disabled by default and add no
measurable overhead when off.

| Tool | Scope | Platform |
|------|-------|----------|
| [pyinstrument v5.1+](https://github.com/joerick/pyinstrument) | CPU profiling (statistical, async-aware) | All |
| [tracemalloc](https://docs.python.org/3/library/tracemalloc.html) (stdlib) | Memory allocation tracking | All |
| SQLAlchemy event hooks | Query timing, N+1 detection, slow query logging | All |
| [web-vitals v4+](https://github.com/GoogleChrome/web-vitals) | Core Web Vitals (CLS, FCP, INP, LCP, TTFB) | Browser |

### File Layout

```
infrastructure/profiling/
├── __init__.py        ← Barrel exports (cpu_profile, memory_snapshot, sql_profile)
├── cpu.py             ← pyinstrument wrapper
├── memory.py          ← tracemalloc wrapper
└── sql.py             ← SQLAlchemy event hooks

ports/api/middleware/
├── profiling.py       ← On-demand per-request CPU profiling (?profile=1 or ?profile=cpu)
└── timing.py          ← Server-Timing header + request duration logging

frontend/src/lib/profiling/
├── index.ts           ← Barrel exports
└── web-vitals.ts      ← Core Web Vitals reporting
```

